# Sample 6: UX Microcopy – Buttons, Errors, and Empty States

**Client Type:** Fictional fintech app ("VaultPay")
**Goal:** Reduce user anxiety during money transfers and clarify confusing error states.

---

### 1. Primary Call-to-Action Buttons (Variations)

| Context | Button Text | Why it works |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Send Money | **Confirm Transfer** | "Confirm" feels safer than "Send" for large amounts. |
| Withdraw Funds | **Withdraw to Bank** | Clarity reduces support tickets about where the money goes. |
| Add Payment Method | **Add Card** | Short, skimmable, obvious. |

---

### 2. Error Messages (Turning Frustration into Action)

**Scenario:** User enters an expired credit card.

**Bad Version:** *"Error. Invalid card."* (Vague, scary.)

**Good Version (What we use):**
> **Oops, that card expired.** 
> Please check the expiration date or try a different card. Your funds are safe—nothing has been charged.

---

**Scenario:** User tries to send $5,000 but has a $2,000 daily limit.

**Bad Version:** *"Transaction declined."* (Panic-inducing.)

**Good Version (What we use):**
> **Daily limit reached.** 
> You can send up to $2,000 per day. Want to split this into multiple days, or verify your ID to raise your limit?
> [Button: Split Payment] | [Button: Verify ID Now]

---

### 3. Empty States (When a user has no data yet)

**Scenario:** User opens the "Transaction History" tab for the first time.

> **Nothing here yet—and that's a good thing.**
> Your first transaction will appear here once you send or receive money. Ready to get started?
> [Button: Send Money]
